age.description: The age range of the people you've reached.

country.description: The countries where the people you've reached are located. This is based on information such as a person's hometown, their current city and the geographical location where they tend to be when they visit Facebook.

gender.description: Gender of people you've reached. People who don't list their gender are shown as 'not specified'.

frequency_value.description: The number of times an ad in your Reach and Frequency campaign was served to each person.

hourly_stats_aggregated_by_advertiser_ti.description: Hourly breakdown aggregated by the time ads were delivered in the advertiser's time zone. For example, if your ads are scheduled to run from 9 AM to 11 AM, but they reach audiences in multiple time zones, they may deliver from 9 AM to 1 PM in the advertiser's time zone. Stats will be aggregated into four groups 9 AM - 10 AM, 10 AM - 11 AM, 11 AM - 12 PM, and 12 PM - 1 PM.

hourly_stats_aggregated_by_audience_time.description: Hourly breakdown aggregated by the time ads were delivered in the audiences' time zone. For example, if your ads are scheduled to run from 9 AM to 11 AM but they reach audiences in multiple time zones, they may deliver from 9 AM to 1 PM in the advertiser's time zone. Stats will be aggregated into two groups 9 AM - 10 AM and 10 AM - 11 AM.

impression_device.description: The device where your last ad was served to someone on Facebook. For example "iPhone" if someone viewed your ad on an iPhone.

place_page_id.description: The id of the place page involved in impression, click or action.

placement.description: Where your ad was served on Facebook, for example on Newsfeed on a mobile device.

product_id.description: The id and name of the product involved in impression, click or action.

region.description: The regions where the people you've reached are located. This is based on information such as a person's hometown, their current city and the geographical location where they tend to be when they visit Facebook.
